      "text": "Notice the contradiction, because it exposes the illusion again: smokers light up when they're devastated and when they're celebrating. A funeral and a wedding. Heartbreak and a promotion. If the cigarette genuinely matched an emotional need, it couldn't possibly fit both grief and joy — they're opposites. What was really happening is what's always happening: any intense moment heightened your awareness of the monster's nagging, and the cigarette relieved that, while your mind credited it to \"handling the emotion.\" The wedding was joyful on its own; the grief was painful on its own; the cigarette changed neither. It just fed the addiction during a vivid moment, so the moment and the cigarette got welded together in memory.\n\nThis is why celebrations can be sneaky-risky even when life is great: the cue is strong and the \"this is a special exception\" thought is seductive. And why grief is risky: someone may literally hand you one \"to help,\" and your own mind offers it as comfort. In both cases, the cigarette delivers only a brief, false boost and then leaves the actual emotion exactly where it was — plus a freshly woken addiction."
