      "title": "Module 2 — Emotions are waves too",
      "text": "The core skill here is affect tolerance — the ability to feel a strong emotion without needing to immediately escape or numb it. It rests on a simple truth: emotions, like cravings, are waves. They rise, peak, and pass on their own if you let them move through you. The problem was never that you couldn't handle feelings — it's that smoking taught you to interrupt them with a drug before they could run their course. Now you get to feel them properly, which is both healthier and, surprisingly, more bearable than the constant low-level interrupting.\n\nWhen a strong emotion comes: name it (\"this is grief,\" \"this is anger,\" \"this is excitement\"), let it be there without rushing to alter it, breathe through it, and let it crest and ease. Negative emotions processed this way actually resolve faster than emotions numbed and deferred. And positive emotions felt fully — without stepping outside to feed a monster — are simply richer. You get more of your own joy back."
